88. Merge Sorted Array
Problem Statement

You are given two sorted arrays:

nums1 of size m + n
nums2 of size n

The first m elements of nums1 are valid elements, while the last n elements are 0 and act as empty spaces.

Merge nums2 into nums1 such that the final array remains sorted.

Example
Input
nums1 = [1,2,3,0,0,0]
m = 3

nums2 = [2,5,6]
n = 3
Output
[1,2,2,3,5,6]
Important Observation

Only first m elements in nums1 are valid.

Actual arrays:

nums1 = [1,2,3]
nums2 = [2,5,6]

The extra zeros are placeholders.

Brute Force Approach
Copy nums2 into nums1
Sort nums1
Complexity
O((m+n) log(m+n))

Not optimal.

Optimal Approach

Since both arrays are already sorted, we can merge them efficiently using the two-pointer technique.

Main Idea

Start filling nums1 from the BACK.

Why?

Because front positions already contain useful elements and may get overwritten.

Pointer Setup
int i = m - 1;

Points to last valid element of nums1.

int j = n - 1;

Points to last element of nums2.

int k = m + n - 1;

Points to last position of nums1.

Visualization
