               i     k

nums2 = [2,5,6]
               j
Java Solution
class Solution {

    public void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {

        int i = m - 1;
        int j = n - 1;
        int k = m + n - 1;

        while (i >= 0 && j >= 0) {

            if (nums1[i] > nums2[j]) {

                nums1[k] = nums1[i];
                i--;

            } else {

                nums1[k] = nums2[j];
                j--;
            }

            k--;
        }

        while (j >= 0) {

            nums1[k] = nums2[j];
            j--;
            k--;
        }
    }
}
Code Explanation
Step 1 — Compare Elements
if (nums1[i] > nums2[j])

Compare the largest remaining elements of both arrays.

Step 2 — Place Larger Element at End

If nums1 element is larger:

nums1[k] = nums1[i];

Else:

nums1[k] = nums2[j];
Step 3 — Move Pointers

After placing an element:

k--;

Move the position pointer left.

Also move either:

i--

or

j--

depending on which element was used.

Why Start from Back?

If we start from front:

nums1 elements may get overwritten

Starting from back avoids this issue because empty spaces are available at the end.

